        "title": "Integration test gaps (none exist today)",
        "content": "1. **End-to-end scan cycle** — real `Store` (tmp_path), mocked HTTP via `httpx.MockTransport`, run `pipeline.run()` twice with a modified second payload: assert run 1 reports everything as `new`, run 2 reports the changed one as `changed` and the rest as neither. This is the one test that would have caught the `content_hash` salary-blind-spot above.\n2. **`sources.yaml` validation against `FETCHERS`** — read the real `sources.yaml`, assert every `ats:` value is a key in `fetchers.FETCHERS`, and every source dict has the required keys its fetcher expects (e.g. `workday` needs `host`/`tenant`/`site`). Cheap test, catches config typos before a scheduled run silently no-ops that source.\n3. **`agent.py db-new` → `db-mark` round trip against a live `Store`** — dump, then mark with the returned `watermark` (not `--now`), then dump again and assert the same rows aren't repeated.\n4. **CLI smoke test** — invoke `cli.py --dry-run` via `subprocess` against a fixture `sources.yaml` pointed at a mock server (or monkeypatched `fetch_all`), assert exit code 0 and that `jobs.db` is untouched.\n5. **CI wiring** — `.github/workflows/scrape.yaml` has no test gate at all; add a separate `on: pull_request` workflow that runs `pytest` before any change can merge, so the credential-gated scrape workflow doesn't become the first place a regression is discovered.\n\n---\n\nIf you'd like, I can scaffold the actual `tests/` directory (`conftest.py`, `pytest.ini`, and the P0 files for `models.py`/`filters.py`/`store.py`) so you have a running baseline rather than just skeletons — say the word and I'll wire it up and run it.",
